ological power that frequently exceeds, both in scope and substance, their associated scriptural records. The essays explore how the Bible’s women are fluidly negotiated and diversely redeployed to offer (conflicting) comment on issues including female authority, speech and sexuality, and in discussions of doctrine, confessional politics, exploration and grief. As it explores the rich ideological currency of the Bible’s women in early modern culture, this volume demonstrates that the Bible’s women are persistently difficult to evade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen in the Bible. 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aEve.  aGenesis.  aNew Testament.  aOld Testament.  aRevelation.  aWhore of Babylon.  abiblical women.  aearly modern Bibles.  aearly modern exegesis.  aearly modern literary culture.  afeminine archetypes.  areligious divisions.1 aBrownlee, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownlee, Victoria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCallaghan, Dympna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallagher, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallagher, Laura, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGroves, Beatrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodgson, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopkins, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOsherow, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRist, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aS